metadata.name: Drifters #74
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #478
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: Truchet Towers #153
metadata.description:
Curved Truchet tiling is laid down on a 3D plane forming an imaginary landscape of ripples.

The longest continuous line created by the tiling is removed, cutting a path through the terrain.
This occurs within 3D space and may or may not appear within the confines of the canvas frame,
but most likely will appear.

A tower rises up to wherever a circle is created by the tiling. Driven by the random
tiling, zero or several of these may appear within the frame. Shadows differ in each mint.

In addition to working on decorative tiling, S√©bastien Truchet worked on canals and sundials,
forming the inspiration for the exploration of shade and shadow in this work.

Mints will have a variety of earth-tone background colors with each perspective of the scene
slightly different to produce diverse results.

As I researched S√©bastien Truchet I learned that he worked with hydraulics and canal design,
as well as sundials. This became the inspiration for my new shading and shadowing technique used
in this piece.

For me this piece evokes a sense of agriculture, and connects me to an imaginary
landscape that could have looked familiar to Truchet in 18th century France.

This work was created with my own javascript, utilizing my polyline path helper library I
maintain at https://github.com/markroland/path-helper.

metadata.name: Antiflow #431
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." -¬†Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about¬†how opposing¬†forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea¬†reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental¬†law of nature baked into the¬†very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise¬†from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing¬†forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique¬†set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio¬†is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.

metadata.name: Tapestry #8
metadata.description:
Tapestry celebrates palettes and texture. It emphasizes the power of palettes by using them in a unique texture with infinite variations.

Tapestry has 136 very distinct palettes, each with it's own (not so secret) backstory.

The mint size of 747 was chosen because that is the expected number of mints required to get at least one of each palette. For anyone interested, this is called the coupon collector problem and has an accurate approximate solution of n * (ln(n) + .577216) + 0.5

Algorithm

The patterns and colors are generated by using parameterized Perlin noise, and a custom algorithm is used for the canvas-like texture. The canvas texture was especially satisfying since it is generated very fast by manipulating the z values with trigonometric functions. This allows Tapestry to render efficiently on any screen size (see the Responsive section below).

Attributes

Palette - each palette has an equal chance of being selected.
Amplitude - determines the overall turbulence in the pattern.
Vertical Variation - the variation in the vertical component of the pattern.
Horizontal Variation - the variation in the horizontal component of the pattern.
Noise Factor - the amount of noise the the overall pattern.
Color Variation - the variation in the color changes.

Rarities

The minting process will sort out the rarities. Since there are only 747 mints for 136 palettes, there will most certainly be some very rare palettes, probably a few with only one mint.

The other attributes produce billions of variations, virtually guaranteeing that each pattern will be entirely unique.

Responsive

Tapestry is responsive and will render on any screen size. Due to it's rendering speed, it's well suited for 4K or larger screens.

Notes

's' saves an image using the exact size of the current window so you can get an image in any resolution.

Since displays vary so widely and Tapestry will work on any any screen size, you can tweak the grain and brightness using the left/right arrow keys (grain), and up/down arrow keys (brightness). 'r' resets the values to the defaults.

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #125
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: Incomlete #57
metadata.description:
Incomplete is normal while complete is unnormal.
Each artwork has one status: Normal, Complete, or Rare.

Even you can pause or rewind the process, you still can't change the incomplete result.
Learn to enjoy the incomplete is the only way. 
Just like your life.

The blocks will move and combine. We could have multiple point of view for the incomplete:
4 different Types according to the distance.
3 level of Stroke for different style.
3 types of Shadow and light.
2 different Materials of blocks.
And 40 selected color Palettes with different amount and angle of blocks

[Interact]
[p] Pause 
[r] Rewind 
[s] Save in PNG 

Made with p5.js
